00:39:41.190 --> 00:39:43.790
Do you remember, we
haven't talked so much

00:39:43.790 --> 00:39:45.680
about Kirchhoff's
voltage law, but I'm

00:39:45.680 --> 00:39:47.610
connecting it with
the discrete case,

00:39:47.610 --> 00:39:51.900
to add in a little more insight.

00:39:51.900 --> 00:39:56.170
What did Kirchhoff's
voltage law say?

00:39:56.170 --> 00:40:01.860
In that case, A was
a difference matrix.

00:40:01.860 --> 00:40:05.070
It was the incidence
matrix for our graph.

00:40:05.070 --> 00:40:12.550
And the question was-- I
have to take two moments

00:40:12.550 --> 00:40:14.270
to think about that.

00:40:14.270 --> 00:40:20.090
So Kirchhoff's voltage
law, for a graph.

00:40:20.090 --> 00:40:22.380
A is an incidence matrix.

00:40:22.380 --> 00:40:30.020
You know, the minus one, one
guys, one for every edge?

00:40:30.020 --> 00:40:38.130
And let me call
it v again, or e.

00:40:38.130 --> 00:40:40.630
I called it e at that time.

00:40:40.630 --> 00:40:44.820
Let's just look at an x.

00:40:44.820 --> 00:40:45.320
Right.

00:40:45.320 --> 00:40:58.920
A is this long thin matrix,
times-- sorry, u's. u's.

00:40:58.920 --> 00:41:04.800
Let me say it all at once.

00:41:04.800 --> 00:41:07.950
Which vectors have the form Au?

00:41:07.950 --> 00:41:13.500
Which vectors are combinations
of the columns of A?

00:41:13.500 --> 00:41:18.980
The test is,
Kirchhoff's voltage law,

00:41:18.980 --> 00:41:23.220
that if I go around any
loop in the graph --

00:41:23.220 --> 00:41:31.060
so if I have a u_1 here, u_2
here, u_5 here, and u_7 here --

00:41:31.060 --> 00:41:35.900
then Au will produce
u_1-u_7 on that edge.

00:41:35.900 --> 00:41:39.030
It'll produce a
u_2-u_1 on that edge.

00:41:39.030 --> 00:41:42.210
It'll produce a
u_5-u_2 on that edge,

00:41:42.210 --> 00:41:45.590
if the edges are
all going that way.

00:41:45.590 --> 00:41:49.530
And it'll produce a
u_7-u_5 on that edge.

00:41:49.530 --> 00:41:56.460
So I've got four components
of Au, four differences.

00:41:56.460 --> 00:41:59.140
And what does Kirchhoff's
voltage law tell me

00:41:59.140 --> 00:42:00.860
about those four differences?

00:42:00.860 --> 00:42:04.730
Which I can certainly
see directly.

00:42:04.730 --> 00:42:12.390
Those four differences, u_1-u_7,
u_2-u_1, u_5-u_2 and u_7-u_5.

00:42:12.390 --> 00:42:16.930
What's the obvious fact
about those four guys?

00:42:16.930 --> 00:42:21.530
They add to zero.

00:42:21.530 --> 00:42:27.560
The total drop around
a loop is zero.

00:42:27.560 --> 00:42:29.980
You see, if I cancel
those, if I add

00:42:29.980 --> 00:42:33.880
them, the u_1's cancel, the
u_2's cancel, the u_5's cancel,

00:42:33.880 --> 00:42:34.980
the u_7's cancel.

00:42:34.980 --> 00:42:35.951
We know this.

00:42:35.951 --> 00:42:36.450
OK.

00:42:36.450 --> 00:42:38.830
So that's Kirchhoff's
voltage law.

00:42:38.830 --> 00:42:46.150
It's got to have
a continuous form.

00:42:46.150 --> 00:42:53.910
This tells me, this is
the test on v at a point.

00:42:53.910 --> 00:42:57.690
What's the test on
v around a loop?

00:42:57.690 --> 00:43:01.110
I just want to connect
that-- I have to connect that

00:43:01.110 --> 00:43:06.900
to a second test.

00:43:06.900 --> 00:43:10.750
I'll just mention it, and
you'll find it in the book.

00:43:10.750 --> 00:43:12.990
That's the pointwise test.

00:43:12.990 --> 00:43:14.760
That was the easy test.

00:43:14.760 --> 00:43:17.880
We applied it to this and
we got the answer yes.

00:43:17.880 --> 00:43:21.160
If it was 3y, 2x, we
got the answer no.

00:43:21.160 --> 00:43:26.070
Now let me give you
a test that looks

00:43:26.070 --> 00:43:28.160
like Kirchhoff's voltage law.

00:43:28.160 --> 00:43:32.170
So I'm going to integrate
around a closed loop.

00:43:32.170 --> 00:43:33.480
What am I going to integrate?

00:43:33.480 --> 00:43:38.970
I think I integrate v--
Oh boy, I'd better look.

00:43:38.970 --> 00:43:41.251
It's easy to get these wrong.

00:43:41.251 --> 00:43:41.750
Yeah.

00:43:41.750 --> 00:43:45.080
So I would call
this the vorticity.

00:43:45.080 --> 00:43:47.110
And then I would
say the vorticity

00:43:47.110 --> 00:43:49.290
is zero for a gradient field.

00:43:49.290 --> 00:43:53.110
Now my integral guy is
going to be the circulation.

00:43:53.110 --> 00:43:53.960
Oh yeah.

00:43:53.960 --> 00:43:55.500
Because I'm following the path.

00:43:55.500 --> 00:44:03.550
So it's just v_1*dx+v_2*dy
should be zero.

00:44:03.550 --> 00:44:08.020
Around every closed loop --
that's idea of this thing,

00:44:08.020 --> 00:44:11.840
that it tells me the integral
goes around a closed loop --

00:44:11.840 --> 00:44:23.370
if I follow the velocity field,
the total circulation is zero.

00:44:23.370 --> 00:44:27.740
I put this up here as a
fact in vector calculus

00:44:27.740 --> 00:44:29.230
that's connected to that.

00:44:29.230 --> 00:44:32.050
These, one is zero
when the other is zero.

00:44:32.050 --> 00:44:34.160
There's a Stokes'
theorem that tells me

00:44:34.160 --> 00:44:38.480
that this integral is found
from a double integral of this.

00:44:38.480 --> 00:44:41.520
So if one is zero,
the other is zero.

00:44:41.520 --> 00:44:45.910
I'm just saying, here
is the natural analog

00:44:45.910 --> 00:44:48.110
of Kirchhoff's voltage law.

00:44:48.110 --> 00:44:49.310
OK.

00:44:49.310 --> 00:44:51.600
I had to say something
about voltage law,

00:44:51.600 --> 00:44:54.440
because for the
divergence, which I'm now

00:44:54.440 --> 00:44:59.910
going to get to-- Whatever.

00:44:59.910 --> 00:45:05.950
Let me ask about
divergence of w equal zero.

00:45:05.950 --> 00:45:10.030
What does that mean?

00:45:10.030 --> 00:45:14.270
That's going to be the
equivalent of whose law?

00:45:14.270 --> 00:45:16.790
Please tell me.

00:45:16.790 --> 00:45:20.200
Which law is going to be the
equivalent of-- Divergence

00:45:20.200 --> 00:45:24.460
of w equal zero is going
to mean there's no source.

00:45:24.460 --> 00:45:27.970
Whatever goes in, comes out.

00:45:27.970 --> 00:45:30.500
Whose law is that?

00:45:30.500 --> 00:45:31.470
That's Kirchhoff again.

00:45:31.470 --> 00:45:33.350
Well, yeah, other
people in physics.

00:45:33.350 --> 00:45:33.850
Right.

00:45:33.850 --> 00:45:38.660
But in our little world,
it's the other Kirchhoff law.

00:45:38.660 --> 00:45:41.750
It's Kirchhoff's current law.

00:45:41.750 --> 00:45:46.740
It's the one, it's the
A transpose, right?

00:45:46.740 --> 00:45:49.620
This is what we're thinking of
as A transpose w equal zero.

00:45:49.620 --> 00:45:55.670
Kirchhoff's current
law, in equals out.

00:45:55.670 --> 00:46:00.190
How will I translate that
in equal out for functions?

00:46:00.190 --> 00:46:05.240
Now I don't have--
On a graph, I just

00:46:05.240 --> 00:46:09.530
had the total flow, the
net flow at every node.

00:46:09.530 --> 00:46:12.990
Notice the divergence
is at every node.

00:46:12.990 --> 00:46:17.640
The circulation was
around every loop.

00:46:17.640 --> 00:46:18.370
OK.

00:46:18.370 --> 00:46:21.720
So in equals out was just
the sum of four things.

00:46:21.720 --> 00:46:25.660
OK, here I'm going
to have in equal

00:46:25.660 --> 00:46:31.250
out-- How am I going to
express in equal out?

00:46:31.250 --> 00:46:33.220
Divergence of w equals 0.

00:46:33.220 --> 00:46:37.380
Yeah, what I need is
the divergence theorem.

00:46:37.380 --> 00:46:41.830
Let's just face it,
we've got to have that.

00:46:41.830 --> 00:46:45.240
So I have a region here.

00:46:45.240 --> 00:46:52.690
I have a w everywhere,
w, [w 1, w 2].

00:46:52.690 --> 00:46:54.060
Then the divergence theorem.

00:46:54.060 --> 00:46:58.150
This is the great
identity, which

00:46:58.150 --> 00:47:00.851
of course has a discrete form.

00:47:00.851 --> 00:47:01.350
OK.

00:47:01.350 --> 00:47:06.880
The divergence theorem says that
if I integrate over the region,

00:47:06.880 --> 00:47:12.280
over this region
R, the divergence,

00:47:12.280 --> 00:47:17.120
that's (dw_1/dx+dw_2/dy), dxdy.

00:47:23.780 --> 00:47:26.545
So that's like
telling me the source,

00:47:26.545 --> 00:47:30.840
I'm integrating over the
source at every point.

00:47:30.840 --> 00:47:38.460
At every point here, this
measures in minus out.

00:47:38.460 --> 00:47:44.480
But now, when I put the whole
thing together by integrating,

00:47:44.480 --> 00:47:47.040
what's the right-hand
side of this equation?

00:47:47.040 --> 00:47:49.800
Do you know the
divergence theorem?

00:47:49.800 --> 00:47:55.390
And let's remember it
and see why it's so.

00:47:55.390 --> 00:48:01.660
What I'm doing is in equals out
for the whole region at once.

00:48:01.660 --> 00:48:02.160
Right?

00:48:02.160 --> 00:48:05.830
When I-- This is like
in equal out at a point.

00:48:05.830 --> 00:48:08.190
But now I'm putting all
the points together.

00:48:08.190 --> 00:48:15.090
So the only way out will be
out through the boundary.

00:48:15.090 --> 00:48:19.450
And so I'll need to
say how much flows out.

00:48:19.450 --> 00:48:25.180
This is the total source, the
total in equal out inside.

00:48:25.180 --> 00:48:28.370
The only way to get out
is through the boundary.

00:48:28.370 --> 00:48:35.650
So this is the integral
around the boundary of-- So

00:48:35.650 --> 00:48:39.730
what's the flow out?

00:48:39.730 --> 00:48:45.610
It's, yeah, it's somehow--
Think now, what should go there?

00:48:45.610 --> 00:48:49.850
This is flux I'm talking about.

00:48:49.850 --> 00:48:53.890
Flux is short word for
the total flow out.

00:48:53.890 --> 00:48:57.260
OK.

00:48:57.260 --> 00:49:02.830
So now I've got
to get this right.

00:49:02.830 --> 00:49:10.510
In vector notation, it would
be-- w tells me the flow.

00:49:10.510 --> 00:49:16.210
But flow outwards, see,
suppose w points that way.

00:49:16.210 --> 00:49:20.080
Then the actual flow
out is not all that.

00:49:20.080 --> 00:49:22.690
Because a lot of that
is just going sideways.

00:49:22.690 --> 00:49:24.230
It's this part.

00:49:24.230 --> 00:49:26.810
It's the flow perpendicular
to the boundary.

00:49:26.810 --> 00:49:33.130
So it's w dot n, the
normal component of flow.

00:49:33.130 --> 00:49:42.070
And I integrate that
around the boundary.

00:49:42.070 --> 00:49:46.190
There you have a
key, key theorem.

00:49:46.190 --> 00:49:51.080
In 2-D. And it's an
equation for the flux.

00:49:51.080 --> 00:49:53.370
It's like the fundamental
theorem of calculus,

00:49:53.370 --> 00:49:58.730
but now we're in two dimensions.

00:49:58.730 --> 00:50:00.260
And this is what it looks like.

00:50:00.260 --> 00:50:05.090
OK, so I'm obviously not going
to finish with the divergence

00:50:05.090 --> 00:50:07.750
theorem today.

00:50:07.750 --> 00:50:10.090
So what's the conclusion?

00:50:10.090 --> 00:50:15.200
If the divergence
is zero, then what?

00:50:15.200 --> 00:50:25.500
If the divergence is zero, if
this is zero at every point,

00:50:25.500 --> 00:50:35.390
then this is zero
across every loop.

00:50:35.390 --> 00:50:38.990
Can I call this thing a loop?

00:50:38.990 --> 00:50:42.500
That closed loop.

00:50:42.500 --> 00:50:49.860
That's the conclusion
that we want to reach.

00:50:49.860 --> 00:50:52.700
So this is the
divergence theorem.

00:50:52.700 --> 00:50:59.660
The text gives a proof,
not to repeat in class,

00:50:59.660 --> 00:51:03.680
but it's a crucial
formula to know.

00:51:03.680 --> 00:51:08.700
That the integral of the
divergence is the flux.

00:51:08.700 --> 00:51:09.450
OK.

